==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /frɪθ/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[frithuz]]'', from Indo-European ''*prāy-, *prēy-'' ‘like, love’. Cognates include Old Frisian ''fretho'', Old Saxon ''frithu'' (Dutch ''[[vrede]]''), Old High German ''[[fridu]]'' (German ''[[Friede]])'', Old Norse ''[[friðr]]'' (Icelandic ''[[friður]]'', Swedish and Danish ''[[fred]]'').  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πραυς]], Common Slavic ''*prijati'' (Old Church Slavonic [[прити]]) and *''[[prijatel]]'' ‘friend’, Old Irish ''ríar'' (Welsh [[rhydd]] ‘free’).
===Noun===
'''friþ'''  ''m'' (-es)

# [[peace]]
# [[refuge]], [[sanctuary]]

